<para>
  Isotropic thermal expansion makes an additive contribution of
  <equation>
    <alt role="tex">
      \[ -C_{ijkl} \alpha_{kl} (T-T_0) \]
    </alt>
  </equation>
  to the <xref linkend="Flux-Stress"/>, where <inlineequation><alt
  role="tex">\(C_{ijkl}\)</alt></inlineequation> is the &material;'s
  <link linkend="PropertyType-Elasticity">elastic</link> modulus, and
  <inlineequation><alt role="tex">\(T\)</alt></inlineequation> is the
  local <xref linkend="Field-Temperature"/> &field;.
</para>
<para>
  <inlineequation><alt role="tex">\(\alpha_{kl}\)</alt></inlineequation>
  is the thermal expansion coefficient, which is a symmetric second
  rank tensor whose diagonal elements, <inlineequation><alt
  role="tex">\(\alpha_{ii}\)</alt></inlineequation>, are equal to the
  parameter <varname>alpha</varname>, and whose off-diagonal elements
  are 0.
</para>
<para>
  <inlineequation><alt role="tex">\(T_0\)</alt></inlineequation> is
  equal to the parameter <varname>T0</varname>.  It is the temperature
  at which the thermal strain vanishes.
</para>

